{"key":"processedPost-18002312","value":{"id":18002312,"first":17999805,"last":18002396,"when":1364127743,"utime":"03/24/13 03:22 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Kalypto said:</strong><br />So if i use agar to isolate one dna strand and make a master jar then more jars and a tub <br />then take the best shroom from that tub and isolate it , the next batch will be the same not better?</blockquote><br />That is not how it's done.<br /><a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Agar-Petri-Dishes\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">On agar</a>, you <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Strain-Isolation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">isolate individual sectors(strains)</a> and grow out each one to fruiting.&nbsp; Before fruiting however, you save a culture from each strain in a <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Master-Culture-Slants\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">master culture slant</a>.&nbsp; Once you grow out and test each strain, you go back to the culture slant of the best performer, and grab young cell lines to continue growing with.<br />A mushroom grown from spores may or may not have multiple strains present.&nbsp; We don't <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mushroom-Cloning\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">clone</a> and isolate these further because they will rarely perform individually as well as they do in tandem.&nbsp; The stellar performing strains are isolated to single sectors on agar and then test fruited.&nbsp; This means you may have 100 jars, all with a different strain, but at least one of those 100 will deliver wall to wall flushes of high quality product. The key is to have the discipline and drive to follow through with it.<br />RR","title":"Re: How many agar isolations is too many?"}}